Notebook[{
Cell["Tarski Geometry Guide", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"9d870de9-3472-4242-9a19-ccc61ba1545f"],

Cell["\<\
First-order axiomatic geometry on graphs, in the style of Alfred Tarski's \
1959 axiomatization. Two primitive relations \\u2014 betweenness and \
equidistance \\u2014 expressed directly as graph-metric predicates; eleven \
axioms expressed as graph predicates; two Tarski-only constructions defined \
without any metric arithmetic.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dfd64b42-7a08-4d8d-a239-6a6bce761318"],

Cell["\<\
Tarski's axiomatization is the most parsimonious classical foundation for \
geometry: only points as objects, only two relations, and eleven first-order \
axioms that recover elementary plane geometry. For the infra-observer on a \
graph, betweenness and equidistance are exactly the relations accessible via \
shortest-path measurements. Every axiom becomes a testable question about the \
graph's metric structure.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dd9cfa11-9e09-4bdc-b3ba-a8ebf781f13f"],

Cell["Primitive Relations", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"e495f609-9fac-4480-b8a9-5440d6ac0733"],

Cell["\<\
The two relations that generate all of Tarski's geometry. Both are defined \
directly from GraphDistance.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"185d4b2e-f1b0-49cd-96a9-7c6cfcb14d9f"],

Cell["\<\
BetweennessQ[graph, a, b, c] returns True when vertex b lies on a geodesic \
from a to c, i.e. when d(a,b) + d(b,c) = d(a,c). This is the graph-metric \
reading of Tarski's B(a,b,c).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d97c127a-9b8c-4e64-b507-0c4006966740"],

Cell["\<\
EquidistanceQ[graph, a, b, c, d] returns True when d(a,b) = d(c,d). This is \
the graph-metric reading of Tarski's ab \\u2261 cd (segment congruence).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dbeb00c6-6d77-4e74-854d-412d3478970b"],

Cell["\<\
MetricInterval[graph, u, v] returns the full set { w : BetweennessQ[graph, u, \
w, v] }, i.e. the union of all u-v geodesics. This is I(u,v) in the Tarski \
literature.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b618f141-cc64-42d8-bbba-d9afe757cba4"],

Cell["Hypermatrix Substrate", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1efedcd0-7981-4746-b102-bf1cdd06b493"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiStructure memoizes the complete Tarski substrate of a graph into a \
single Association. This makes repeated axiom queries fast: the distance \
matrix and betweenness tensor are computed once.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"20fb175e-11f6-4fa3-bcb5-bd80affbed0c"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiStructure[graph] returns an Association with keys Vertices, \
VertexIndex, Distances, Betweenness, Equidistance, and Diameter.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c119a8f7-a8f6-4a47-af3e-ba90e5725461"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiBetweennessTensor[graph] projects out the sparse rank-3 tensor B[i,j,k] \
= 1 iff B(v_i, v_j, v_k). Sparse on most graphs; the NonzeroPositions are the \
betweenness witnesses.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c48ac92e-8906-4396-b864-5b45099c774e"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiEquidistanceClasses[graph] projects out the partition of unordered \
vertex pairs by distance value. Checking ab \\u2261 cd is a partition lookup \
rather than an n^4 scan.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e1b4dc4f-1d1b-4396-a6e0-6f4a2e2bea2e"],

Cell["Axiom Predicates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"935ad9b4-1c02-481f-b0f3-73685762ef79"],

Cell["\<\
Each of the eleven Tarski axioms is a first-class predicate. \
TarskiAxiomQ[graph] composes all eleven into a dashboard Association.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fa6a4c28-6a96-4a60-9772-429ce55e08d8"],

Cell["\<\
Always True on any connected undirected simple graph (trivial axioms)\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"dbf44ed7-8564-4894-9698-a7de40ae609d"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiCongruenceReflexivityQ: A1 \\u2014 ab \\u2261 ba. Distance is symmetric.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"72fc864c-0403-468c-9a52-6832e5d096e7"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiCongruenceTransitivityQ: A2 \\u2014 transitivity of equidistance. \
Tautology of equality; returns True without scanning.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"edce461e-c56d-4539-9483-53fb85730ff2"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiCongruenceIdentityQ: A3 \\u2014 ab \\u2261 cc implies a = b. Distance \
zero only for the same vertex.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9ea629ce-68b1-45f1-9456-8ad1fa251d37"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiBetweennessIdentityQ: A6 \\u2014 B(a,b,a) implies a = b. Betweenness \
forces 2d(a,b) = 0.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c5bade4e-8e30-4a1b-bf82-441bd8f795d2"],

Cell["Always False on any finite graph (structural failures)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b80859a3-0193-414c-b426-21e70c25b7cb"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiSegmentConstructionQ: A4 \\u2014 every segment can be freely extended \
to any prescribed length. False on all finite graphs: the substrate is \
bounded and cannot always provide the required vertex.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4551681d-6ee8-4767-bebd-02406a8c532a"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiContinuityQ: A11 \\u2014 first-order Dedekind completeness. \
Structurally unsatisfiable on any finite discrete graph. The failure has no \
finite vertex-tuple witness.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9eace87b-2186-4fc8-8689-23f582c893f3"],

Cell["Geometrically interesting (graph-dependent) axioms", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"600145c3-e200-4e01-86cb-759adea893b7"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiFiveSegmentsQ: A5 \\u2014 a triangle-congruence theorem. True on median \
graphs (trees, hypercubes); fails on graphs with non-unique geodesics or \
mismatched distance multiplicities.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8628ef7d-19c5-4e73-a67b-65c7098e9008"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiInnerPaschQ: A7 \\u2014 if B(a,p,c) and B(b,q,c) then there exists x in \
I(p,b) intersect I(q,a). The median-graph axiom in disguise. True on paths, \
cycles, grids, hypercubes; False on the Petersen graph.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"44adb5fd-d276-4daa-8451-2d042450aa18"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiLowerDimensionQ: A8 \\u2014 there exist three non-collinear points. \
False only on path-like (1-dimensional) graphs.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4049e37f-91cd-4c72-9056-d3d69822fa20"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiUpperDimensionQ: A9 \\u2014 three points equidistant from two distinct \
points must be collinear. Fails on hypercubes and grids of effective \
dimension 3 or more.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ee96b15c-deba-4095-8bf4-b1903a4d7c2b"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiEuclidAxiomQ: A10 \\u2014 the parallel postulate in Tarski's \
betweenness/equidistance formulation. Currently returns Indeterminate pending \
the Gupta perpendicular-foot construction.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b4478074-a435-405c-93eb-22d410abb69c"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiAxiomQ: convenience dashboard \\u2014 returns all eleven results as a \
single Association keyed by descriptive axiom names.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"514795fa-ff77-454b-8f7a-63e2bf142af7"],

Cell["Counterexample Finders", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8eba7b0f-7f67-4c2a-adf4-db1291e18b77"],

Cell["\<\
For every universal axiom, FindTarskiCounterexample returns explicit vertex \
tuples that witness the failure. The standard strict / UpTo[n] / All triple \
applies.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2d0be0b8-c6c4-4655-8678-17320afb0707"],

Cell["\<\
FindTarskiCounterexample[graph, TarskiInnerPaschQ, UpTo[1]] returns one \
5-tuple (a,b,c,p,q) for which the betweenness premises hold but the interval \
intersection is empty.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9c8667a8-3f32-49e0-b494-481bef9f8b28"],

Cell["\<\
FindTarskiCounterexample[graph, TarskiSegmentConstructionQ, All] returns \
every 4-tuple (a,b,c,d) for which no segment extension exists.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e9c710d8-63df-4a65-bd81-d12289ce9c70"],

Cell["\<\
FindTarskiCounterexample[graph, TarskiContinuityQ] issues \
FindTarskiCounterexample::nowitness and returns $Failed: A11 has no finite \
witness.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"bfb4e6f5-a470-4b2b-ba82-3b8bb1754cdc"],

Cell["Constructions from B and E", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"67464bdc-7f74-4129-b011-3b673172860c"],

Cell["\<\
Two Tarski-style constructions defined purely from betweenness and \
equidistance. No metric centrality, no Method dispatch, no interval-center \
heuristics. The key contrast: these impose stricter conditions than the \
metric-layer Find* counterparts.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cce03d12-cc8b-400c-974e-2e4c0de3df50"],

Cell["\<\
ExtendSegment[graph, a, b, c, d] finds a vertex x with B(a,b,x) \
and d(b,x) = d(c,d). The A4 witness finder. Returns InfraPoint[{}] when no \
such vertex exists on the graph.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"12500900-ab73-4b3d-9260-c0df1a8cca8a"],

Cell["\<\
FindReflection[graph, x, a] finds vertices x' with B(x,a,x') and d(a,x) \
= d(a,x'): the reflection of x through a. Multi-valued on graphs with \
multiple geodesic continuations.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"922b574b-c588-44e6-a881-2636bf2d372a"],

Cell["\<\
FindMidpoint[graph, a, b] finds vertices m with B(a,m,b) and d(a,m) = \
d(m,b). Returns InfraPoint[{}] for odd-distance pairs \\u2014 no synthetic \
midpoint exists. This is the fundamental difference from FindMidpoint, which \
always returns a central interval element.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"aa082b02-cfd8-48a1-acfd-92ea4d3bae30"],

Cell["Tutorial", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"9fb58b6e-0d8c-4974-aa4a-c268661f11c2"],

Cell["\<\
TarskiGeometryTutorial provides a runnable substrate panel, worked examples for \
every axiom predicate, counterexample extraction on the Petersen graph, and a \
side-by-side comparison of FindMidpoint versus FindMidpoint.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dd449ec1-b930-47c2-8a85-d7bdcb9fc4d3"]
},
FrontEndVersion->"14.3 for Mac OS X ARM (64-bit) (July 8, 2025)",
StyleDefinitions->"Default.nb",
ExpressionUUID->"4683f7b6-aed1-4b1d-ba35-fce7a84eba6f"
]
